segments.text: And for example, we've already addressed this question about integration of the services.
As far as you're concerned, it was a very good move to integrate the services and have integrated units.
What about women in the service?
Now, women have expanded rapidly since the 1960s.
And now I guess they're, I can't remember what percent.
I think about 12% was it to the military?
What's your opinion?
I think it's good.
I really do.
Because I think there are many, many billets in the military that can adequately be filled by women.
I don't see women in a combat role.
I don't want to see women flying fighter aircraft, even though they're capable of doing it.
I can see women flying transport aircraft.
I think they're probably easy, probably 10% of the spaces in the military can be adequately filled by women.
I'm all for it.
I really am.
If we do have selective service in the future, do you think women should be drafted?
Well, with all the pressure on ERA, they want to do their thing.
Yeah, I think so.
I really do.
I think some of them would feel slighted if they weren't drafted.
Okay.
What about the idea of the draft itself?
Do you support reinstituting the draft?
Do you think the voluntary service has failed?
I think the voluntary service to a great extent has failed.
It's improved a little bit recently.
But I think that to an overall extent, I think the volunteer strength has failed because we don't have the level of competency
in our enlisted personnel today in the volunteer army that we ought to have.
The weapon systems and everything has become exceedingly more complicated and more sophisticated.
Even our logistics systems where we're preparing a requisition on a computer where we're getting a computer transmitted requisition and a printout
And everything is very sophisticated, and even automated warehouses.
Well, you've got to have somebody with a level of intelligence and a level of competency that can respond to that.
Otherwise, you're going to create chaos.
So I think that the volunteer army from that standpoint has failed.

The volunteer army has been responsible, and I'm not speaking in a prejudiced vein when I say this, for bringing in a real high percentage of black personnel who just have not had maybe the opportunity for education and training that their
that the average cut of the white young man has had.
For the result, we've got a lot of uneducated blacks in the service that are just not capable of running even a sophisticated vehicle like a tank that's got a little computer in it.
The new Abrams tank has a computer.
The fire control is computer directed.
And hell, you've got to have somebody with at least a high school education to understand and operate the thing.
High school plus a 12-week tech military schooling course to be able to even function the thing.
So I think that we ought to have a draft.
And I think it's got to be better run than it was before.
We had too many possibilities for deferment to where it was strictly a poor man's draft or somebody that wasn't in graduate school or college that could get a deferment.
And those are tough questions.
And they're unpopular questions.
But that's my basic feeling about them.
Okay, let's ask some of the same questions about what's happened in Texas A&M during the 1960s, which happened, of course, under the Rutter regime.
How about ending the mandatory Corps of Cadets?
What's your feeling toward that?
I think sooner or later it had to come with the attitude of the country, you know?
And because we went a long way anti-military, a lot of schools that had ROTCs for a hundred years abandoned them like Harvard, places like that.
I think it had to come sooner or later.
I hated to see it come, but I think it had to come.
And I don't really
I wish they would make a stronger effort to have a stronger core and a little bigger core.
But I guess the core now is about the same size it was when I was in school.
We had about 3,000, a little under 3,000 when I was in school.
It's about 2,300 now?
I think it had to come sooner or later.
What about admitting women are blacks?
I think it's okay.
I think the growth at Texas A&M has been, maybe it hasn't had time to digest the growth that they had, but it's been dynamic and massive.
And I think it is really on the threshold of being
one of the major institutions in the country from an academic standpoint and many other standpoints.
Finally, let's talk about one other topic that the military's written volumes on, and that's leadership.
The what?
The military's written volumes on, and that's leadership.
Yeah.
If you were going down to Texas A&M and invited to give the Corps of Cadets a lecture on how to become a leader,
What would you tell them?
What would I tell them?
What I'd tell them first, they have to be able to lead themselves.
They have to have, they have to have values that they feel that they can live by.
They have to have the courage of their convictions.
They have to
have a sense of humility and a sense of feeling to respect the dignity of everybody that they're associated with and everybody in their command, if they're going to command.
Because every mortal, I think, has a personal human dignity that should be respected.
And then I think they've got to exude

effort and extra effort and above all I think you've got to be honest and you've got to have personal integrity it's hard to define you know what the principles of leadership are but I think if you have your own values in order and know what you want to do with yourself
I believe you can lead others if you can lead yourself.
What type of leader were you?
Well, I think I was a pretty good leader.
A lot of people would say, I know many times I'd have guys tell me, God damn, you're sure a salesman.
You can, in a meeting, you can just sell these guys and make them do anything and they'll just follow you to hell.
You can make a million dollars being a salesman.
And maybe I was a salesman, maybe I was a con man, but I didn't feel like it.
I felt sincere in what I was doing.
And of course there's some old cliches about leadership.
Don't ask anybody to do anything that you wouldn't do yourself.
I think that's a little bit true, but sometimes as a leader, particularly in the military,
You are put in a position sometimes of asking people to do things that you can't do yourself or you're not in a position to do yourself.
So maybe that cliche doesn't apply universally, but I think basically a leader ought to be one that could easily say, follow me or something like that.
When looking back over your military career,

Was there a certain position that you thought was the highlight, a certain place where you felt that this is, this is it, I'm really doing my greatest accomplishments are here at this, at this moment?
Was, was, what was that?
What job was that or when was that?
In Germany, the Gieen, particularly during the airlift.
Yeah.
Looking back over your life, everybody has accomplishments and everybody has shortcomings.
In your military career, what do you think were the accomplishments and what were the shortcomings?
Something that you couldn't finish the job or you just couldn't get done or maybe it wasn't your fault, but you just couldn't do it.
it's hard to say.
Like I say, I use an expression from Churchill, I think that during the Berlin Airlift was my finest hour as far as that's concerned.
But I think the biggest accomplishment I made was really, and it may not, we haven't, we've hardly talked about it, but I think it was
aviation fuel safety.
I really believe that.

And my name is not on that many regulations that have been perpetuated and my name is not associated with that many manuals because no military man's name is in any manuals, but I think I really made an impact on the safety

of aviation fuels and the safety of all fuels, but particularly aviation fuels, that has made a significant impact in military aviation, safety in military aviation, and the spill-off in commercial aviation.
Are you sure?
I think that's really the biggest
If I was going to look back on it, like maybe in the hereafter, St. Peter would say, well what was the best thing you did?
I think that's what I'd tell him.
What about shortcomings?
The shortcomings, the biggest frustration I had in the shortcomings was in Japan, where those old Japanese facilities, they were beautiful, but they were
antiquated in that there was only one six-inch line into and out of these huge underground storage tanks.

And to discharge a tanker into one of those things, particularly a modern, and we began to get the first of the super tankers in those days, the Orion class that had 300,000 barrels on them, it would take us
72 hours to discharge that tanker because of just one entry into it only one line coming off whereas the demurrage it costs six seven thousand dollars a day for that tanker to sit there and pump off
So I immediately started to scrounge pipe and scrounge everything and put more entries into the tanks so that we could put four or five hoses on these tankers.
And I finally got several of the terminals worked up to where we could discharge one of those little mini super tankers in about 12 hours to where the crews would just rebel because they'd

generally think they're gonna have three or four days of liberty after they got from the Middle East to shack up in Japan and we were ready for them to turn around in 12 hours and then I replaced a pipeline on the beach and but I ran constantly into

into command problems they wouldn't wouldn't let me use the pipe and this regulation and that regulation and several times i violated the regulations and they'd send the ig down and make an investigation and he'd always side with me and it was a very frustrating thing and i was not able to finish what i wanted to do over there to really make them into efficient

petroleum handling operation I was able to get about four of the terminals converted and they've since in the four, five, eight, ten years afterwards I left there about putting out finally on contract and everything they were able to modernize some of them but at a considerable expense and we could have done it with our own in-house personnel because we had it all engineered.
We had figured it in the hydraulics of it and everything and
The excess pipe was there, left over from Korea, and all we had to do was get it over there and use the GIs and the Japanese to do it.
And this was the most frustrating thing that I had.
Well, we've talked about your early years, your education, military career, and something about your retirement, your views on the military and on A&M.
Is there something else that I've missed?
No, no.
I believe, and I'm kind of a workaholic, I guess.
I've been called that by my wife and others.
Well, that's obvious because you're one of the very few men that I've met who have been retired that have a full-time job, especially a man who's 70.
I'll be 70 in December and I plan to
I would like to continue, the good Lord willing, what I'm doing now for, you know, five or six more years.
I know men who are generals and are 55 and they play golf three times a week and that's all.
Most of them will be dead in about another five or six years, too.
Well, that could be.
But I've met, I've interviewed a number of those men and they don't seem to have very many interests.
I feel sorry for them because they're
They're out of the mainstream, and they're making no contribution to the society today.
And it can be very satisfying, as well as rewarding.
And I'm not pretentious or anything, but I've done very well.
And it's been very financially rewarding.
And I'm not crazy about money.
I enjoy it.
I spend it wisely and I give to the arts.
I support the arts and charity.
I really feel sorry for these guys that retire and sit on their ass and think the world owes them a living.
I'd like to say that, and I can say as of this point in time right now, that since I've retired,
I've paid on the average of at least twice as much in income tax as I've received in retired pay.
And last year, it was considerably more than that.
And it's kind of a good feeling.
That's unusual for a man to say that paying high taxes is
a good feeling, especially when we have so many people in Washington today denying that they have...
It's a good feeling to know that you're able to do it and that you're able, that you have the good fortune and the good health to be able to do it.
To be so productive.
To be productive enough and to enjoy what you're doing and still not be chagrined by it.
And I don't...

don't you know I think of course I think some taxes and can get to where they're prohibitive and almost confiscatory but I think sometimes it's it's a privilege to be able to pay to pay taxes if you're able to make it and make it fairly and squarely so I don't want to do anything that's immoral or illegal
And I have not done anything that's immoral or illegal.
And this is the way that I want to conduct my business.
It's the way I tried to conduct my military career.
But I really feel sorry for those goddamn senior guys that retire.
And some of them, nearly all of them, want to get a job right after they retire.
But they want to be handed a job making $50,000 a year.
sitting at a big fancy desk in a big fancy office with a few papers coming in and out and not getting their hands dirty.
This is what their thought is.
And you can't do it.
And I was handed a job like that with Scott Paper, but I was constantly on the go and down in the plants and everything.
And it was kind of tough to come into an organization
at the vice president level, when guys that had been working for 20 years that weren't vice presidents, it was kind of tough.
And it was a lot of strained feelings.
And I had to make friends and influence people.
I had to use Dale Carnegie techniques.
And I succeeded in a lot of cases.
There were two or three guys I never did make much headway with.
But I enjoyed it, and I think it really primed me
be able to go then to a small business.
Well, thanks a lot for this interview.
Okay, well it's been fun.
I haven't had the opportunity to purge myself of some of these thoughts in a long, long time, and I hope it will sound interesting enough for you to use.
Oh, yeah.
